Here's a complete example that demonstrates **method hiding** (not overriding) with static methods.

```java
class A {
    static void display() {
        System.out.println("Static method of class A");
    }
}

class B extends A {

    // This is Method Hiding, NOT Overriding
    static void display() {
        System.out.println("Static method of class B");
    }
}

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        A obj1 = new A();
        obj1.display();

        B obj2 = new B();
        obj2.display();

        A obj3 = new B();
        obj3.display();

        A.display();
        B.display();
    }
}
```

### Output

```text
Static method of class A
Static method of class B
Static method of class A
Static method of class A
Static method of class B
```

### Explanation

* `obj1.display();` → Calls `A.display()`
* `obj2.display();` → Calls `B.display()`
* `A obj3 = new B(); obj3.display();` → Calls `A.display()` because **static methods are resolved using the reference type (`A`)**, not the object type (`B`).
* `A.display();` → Calls `A.display()`
* `B.display();` → Calls `B.display()`

---

### Using `@Override` (Compile-Time Error)

