	  so by using interface we can resolve this ambiguity problem.
	  so in interface we can call default/complete method from interface name this will resolve the 
	  ambiguity problem.
      call like this  - A.super.test(); // here A is a interface and test() is a default/complete method 
      in interface  	  
	  
	  code  : 
		  interface A {
			default void test() {
				System.out.println("Test method from Interface A");
			}
	      }

			interface B {
				default void test() {
					System.out.println("Test method from Interface B");
				}
			}

		class C implements A, B {
			// Overriding the test method in class C to avoid ambiguity
			@Override
			public void test() {
				System.out.println("Test method from Class C");
				A.super.test();  // Explicitly calling the test method from Interface A
				B.super.test();  // Explicitly calling the test method from Interface B
			}
		}

		public class Main {
			public static void main(String[] args) {
				C obj = new C();
				obj.test();  // Calls the overridden method in C and also calls A.super.test() and B.super.test()
			}
		}

	  
