Q : Why are interface methods public by default and why are private methods introduced in Java 9? Why can’t we use protected or default access modifiers in interfaces?
Ans : 
- Interface methods are public by default because interfaces define rules that implementing classes must access and implement.
- protected, default(package-private), and private access modifiers were not allowed till Java 8 because interface methods should be accessible everywhere.
- Private methods were introduced in Java 9 to write common internal/helper logic inside interfaces and avoid duplicate code.

Q : after java 9 still default and protected access spoecifiesr still not used in interface why ? 
Ans : 
* Interfaces define rules/contracts for implementing classes.
* So interface methods should be accessible everywhere.
