## 🟦 **3. Polymorphism – “Same method, different behaviour”**

You might have methods like:

```java
Room room = new DeluxeRoom();
room.calculatePrice();
```

Each room type calculates price differently.

Or actions like:

```java
User user = new Admin();
user.login();
```

👉 **Interview-style answer:**

“I used polymorphism mainly for price calculation and room operations. Different room types calculate the price differently, but the method name is the same — `calculatePrice()`. So the correct method runs based on the object type.”

---
Coding example : 
// Parent Class
class Room {
    double basePrice;

    Room(double basePrice) {
        this.basePrice = basePrice;
    }

    // Method to be overridden
    double calculatePrice() {
        return basePrice;
    }
}

// Child Class 1
class DeluxeRoom extends Room {

    DeluxeRoom(double basePrice) {
        super(basePrice);
    }

    @Override
    double calculatePrice() {
        return basePrice + 500;   // extra charge for deluxe
    }
}

// Child Class 2
class SuiteRoom extends Room {

    SuiteRoom(double basePrice) {
        super(basePrice);
    }

    @Override
    double calculatePrice() {
        return basePrice + 1500;  // extra charge for suite
    }
}


// Testing Polymorphism
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Room room1 = new DeluxeRoom(3000);  // parent reference → child object
        Room room2 = new SuiteRoom(3000);   // parent reference → child object

        System.out.println("Deluxe Room Price: " + room1.calculatePrice());
        System.out.println("Suite Room Price: " + room2.calculatePrice());
    }
}


## 🟦 **4. Abstraction – “Showing only what is needed”**

You can have an interface like:

```java
interface PaymentService {
    void pay();
}
```

And different payment types:

* `CardPayment`
* `UPIPayment`

Or an abstract class:

```java
abstract class Room {
    abstract double calculatePrice();
}
```

👉 **Interview-style answer:**

“I used abstraction through interfaces and abstract classes. For example, I created a `PaymentService` interface. The user doesn’t care how card or UPI payment works internally; they just call `pay()`. This hides the complexity.”

---

Coding example : 
// Abstraction using Interface
interface PaymentService {
    void pay(double amount);   // user only knows this method!
}

// Implementation 1: Card Payment
class CardPayment implements PaymentService {

    @Override
    public void pay(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Processing card payment of ₹" + amount);
        // internal logic hidden from user
        System.out.println("Card payment successful!");
    }
}

// Implementation 2: UPI Payment
class UpiPayment implements PaymentService {

    @Override
    public void pay(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Processing UPI payment of ₹" + amount);
        // internal logic hidden from user
        System.out.println("UPI payment successful!");
    }
}

// Main class to run
public class PaymentDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        PaymentService payment1 = new CardPayment(); // abstraction
        payment1.pay(1500);

        System.out.println();

        PaymentService payment2 = new UpiPayment();  // abstraction
        payment2.pay(1500);
    }
}



